An animal they say inhabits the Koranwarabin range - head & make like a man only much [p..?] eyes like stars for brightness, but appears very large - they live in the ground, holes of rocks and caves - Black fellows are very much frightened of them & do not frequent those ranges - Worworong was the last that saw one & he fired several shots at one & hit it but made no impression, nor did it run away or was frightened - The blacks say that this animal formerly used to go about, and where ever Blacks were encamped would go round make water on all their fires put them out and go away

cell.hi: ["On Rising in the Morning" 01] Awake ! get up, get up, get up !
["On Rising in the Morning" 02] Get up and make the fire, the sun is high
["On Rising in the Morning" 03] I will get up directly, stop, stop my trowzers are wet.
Murrumbeek kommergee tudan; burra, burra Murrumbiek Tarrunarlook Tulgunner.
["On Rising in the Morning" 04] You are lazy, get up, chop some wood, make a fire and dry them
Tandum Murrumbīnna Kommargee Tibenner Kulk, Werregut Veīn bar Bidderup Nge

p.hi: ["On Rising in the Morning" 05] What for you tell lie, sun only little up,

cell.hi: Wenerra wa Moyutpin Murrumbinna, Ngervein tinde Wyebo, Winda Tailwork
["On Rising in the Morning" 06] Tailwork nier bedderup, name who leave it on the ground last night.
Tailwork is wet, Nerreno Welain Narlum-boon nge Buker Borun Mola Molar
["On Rising in the Morning" 07] Now it is dry, go on, rub away, ah I see smoke, fire soon come.
Netbo Bedderup; ure, Purrumbon. Ah! Ngeren Port; molocho Vein womon.
["On Rising in the Morning" 08] Very good now, big one fire, now sit down and smoke your pipe.
Marnameek netbo, bullito vein; narlumby Prombean pipe.
["On Rising in the Morning" 09] All good white men when they get up say their prayers, and thank God for takin care of them all night.
Bondup hommogeeker Umarko, Nerdoit kommergee Pardogurrabun, bar thank Pundgil Marman, tuduk kunununner Nerrimbee borund[ut/ap].
["On Rising in the Morning" 10] Big one stupid me and all blackfellows, no like it white man.

p123 "On Eating and Drinking" [Cf Thomas in Smyth (1876:129)]

cell.hi: [“On Eating and Drinking” 01] Put the pannikin on the fire. Where is the tea and sugar ?
Korourk pannikin Veinoit, Winda morrador bar gaem-gaem ?
[“On Eating and Drinking” 02] There is no water, tell the Lubras to get some water, Pannican in Miam.
Nier parn. Toombergee bagrook wantagee parn; Pannican Willumut.
[“On Eating and Drinking” 03] I cannot see pannican; it is not in the Mīam, I have look’d all about.
Nier Pannican Ngerren murrumbeek, Nier kuding Willum, Yarkuneit
[“On Eating and Drinking” 04] Oh me big one stoopid it is behind the Miam by that Gum tree.
Wongurrunin murrumbeek, Miring Willum Karbe nge Beal Turrun.
[“On Eating and Drinking” 05] Wash the Pannican, very good clean, no good dirty.
Kurworbun Pannican, Marnameek Kerwoneit, nillam kunnit pin.
[“On Eating and Drinking” 06] Me big one hungry, where is the kangaroo, the opossum, and Bandicoot ?
Nerrebrunin bullito murrumbeek, Windowring Koem, Waller Wallert, bar Bōōng ?
[“On Eating and Drinking” 07] There they are, also the bear, wallaby, and wombat put them all to the fire, plenty of food in the Bag sit down to-day no gago & look out, only eat and sleep and sing.
Notto nangeit, bar Wimbi, Warren, Turnanuk umarko, Bullito Tanganan quomba Boollaminin, narlumby Yellenewa, utur Koonde Tanganan tinde Tanganan, Yemen bar Yengerk.
[“On Eating and Drinking” 08] Here Pickaniny give that to the Lubras, and tell them when they have eat, to go and look out Gum for blackfellows.
Wa Bopup, Kunuk kunne Bagrook, tombanna Bagrook tinderbeek Tunganan, dado koonde kurrun, Tuduk Koolīnner.

row.cell: [“On Eating and Drinking” 09] This kangaroo is very good, it is a Joè; here is another monmondiek
Kunnee koem marnameek, Joè kargee; bar unngho monmondeek
[“On Eating and Drinking” 10] The water Boils put in the Tea and give some to the children and they fetch us more water.
Parn touloppun, quomba Morador, bar umarleek bopup, tudan bopup wantagee parn uungho
[“On Eating and Drinking” 11] You too much greedy bopup you give some of that kangaroo to that pickaninny out there.
Bulletgarn murrumbinna Bopup; umerleek bopup monkyne nge Tanganun Koem
[“On Eating and Drinking” 12] Now Sleep no you make a noise Boys you play out there. Big one bellyful me.
Yemena Netbo, Dit koody bopup, bopup tillutkerin Monkyn nge, Bullito marp murrumbeek.

[“On Corroboree” 11] You hear Borenuptune Yengerin and Lubras Tonboroner Belp, and the fires all burning go now

div.p: "On going a Journey" [Cf Thomas in Smyth (1876:128]

cell.hi: [“On going a Journey” 01] Now, my blackfellows, make haste and get your breakfast; we will be going.
Eur barbullin kunarkut yanner bullen kunnee wat; kunney wat.
[“On going a Journey” 02] Q. Where are the bullocks ?
Q. Wīnda Wotterring, or wīnda bulgana
[“On going a Journey” 03] A. Over there, behind that hill
[“On going a Journey” 04] Q. Did you see their tracks ?
[“On going a Journey” 05] A. Yes; I saw them this morning
[“On going a Journey” 06] Q. Where did they bed last night ?
[“On going a Journey” 07] A. By the big tree; don't you see their dung ?
A. Narnnarlonniart Karlto; Kudallin Tarrun Kunar?
[“On going a Journey” 08] Go and fetch them that’s a good fellow I will lend you my horse
[“On going a Journey” 09] A. Very well, where bridle & saddle, I will go and fetch them; put my bag in the cart.
Kungargewat, Worong kudeto Narkudedo, nunneiek pelam minebuk, ngargee karber
[“On going a Journey” 10] Now get the things together, Where are the Panicans? Don’t leave anything behind.
Perkart yarrite kitherbă. Windowring turnuk tumart nowvolumbunner turnuk yarrite.
[“On going a Journey” 11] Here’s the bullocks you are a good fellow Bugup here is a stick of tobacco for you.
Mihu pinnuk tuddeyoul kungewă boondarp, Buggup modeyanner kunnunne nurromanner.
[“On going a Journey” 12] Now, blackfellows, hold up the pole of the dray, and two of you hold on the back of the cart.
Netbo tarmbar kartee kulgo, bengeronewat mummedo karter.

[“On going a Journey” 13] There, now, that will do; I will not [have so many things put on the cart, too much bush - you lubras are lazy carry your own bags and rubbish they shall not go stinking on the cart - let there be room in the middle for the little children and the two old men]

Nogeballing, nogeballing; Kanballing [Koodip Yarrite Wondicut Uung Yarrite, wonderbee yarradinna koodar Barnbern kooding - Utur narlumboon kartut Yarrite wootkunununun, alumbanan tinde bengero wagabil koolin bar bopup]

] We will play at ball, you make it up, very high, don't you see one, very good that one, go on kick.
Mangut marnameek, Mongun Ganbony Murrumbinna, Marnameek Kunnup; Ure, Ure kurruk, Nīer Ngarrein Karboit nge.
] Come come make haste me get it
] Take care of the child, no me throw it down; no me
Tartbuk Bopup; Niup Badun Umite Nier wongrunin murrumbeek.
] Throw it out further, do it again very good, call the boys outside.
Umark Worreder, Weatbuk, marnameek Tombargee Bopup Millarree.
] Take care of the stumps, take care, you go on too fast.
Worregerry Kulk, Worregerry Kukkerbrook, Kulberlin Woovoneit murrumbinna.
] Nogee nogee Ball is broke, sit down by and bye play
No more, that will do, mangut tinderbeek narlumby, moloko uungo
] Play at soldiers (policemen). Come here stand up. Hold up your head, hold down your head, that will do, that will do.
Tillutkerin policemen. Warra wee terredee, kommergally, ber[p]ungally, Nogee, [no]gee, nogeemy.

Vocabulary - "Games, Dances" [this page is entirely crossed out]

row.cell: This is a perfect athletic game - a party of young men will assemble, seat themselves in different groups one will rise, throw dust towards another group as a challenge, the challenge is accepted & commences by each party puting hands on the shoulders of his adversary, a strugle for mastery commences, & it is some time ere one is flour'd who immediately returns to his party in general exhausted not able to speak for some seconds --- they early teach their children this useful (& for them) necessary game. ([footnote:] “I have two other words for this: Worork[m]inderneit, Workern[d]erneit”)
Corrobery , there are many kinds of corroberie
a day corrobery or dance named from Bu[tterfly?]
